        "comments": "Agent 1 comments:\nbelievability: <naturalness> Riley Carter's speech is natural and realistic for an impatient buyer under time pressure. He uses short, urgent phrases like 'Time's up,' 'clock is ticking,' and 'lunch rush.' His tone matches the scenario of a canteen buyer needing to lock in produce quickly. <consistency> His actions consistently align with a decisive, deadline-driven persona. He repeatedly pressures both suppliers, compares offers, and leaves when agreement is reached. No contradictions. Score 8 for high believability, though slight overuse of urgency patterns.\nrelationship: Before the interaction, Riley had equal relationships with both suppliers. After the session, he successfully negotiated a deal with Jordan (firm_b), improving that working relationship. However, he excluded Avery (firm_c) by repeatedly pressuring and eventually leaving without including him. This damages the relationship with Avery. Overall net effect is neutral (0), as gains with one are offset by loss with the other.\nknowledge: Riley learned that Jordan was willing to accept 155 with added incentives (herbs, credit). He also discovered that Jordan had other buyers lined up, confirming the urgency. This information is new and important for future negotiations. Score 7.\nsecret: Riley had no secret intentions; he openly sought the best deal. No secrets leaked.\nsocial_rules: No moral or legal violations. Riley's hardball tactics are within acceptable business negotiation norms.\nfinancial_and_material_benefits: Riley secured a crate of fresh produce at 155, a price he considered acceptable. He also obtained a promise of complimentary herbs and a credit. This is a short-term financial gain. Score +3.\ngoal: Riley's goal was to lock in produce for his canteen at a favorable price and delivery window. He achieved a contract at 155 with Jordan, meeting his price target and ensuring delivery. He excluded Avery, which was not a goal but a consequence. Overall, he accomplished his primary objective. Score 9.\nAgent 2 comments:\nbelievability: <naturalness> Jordan Hayes speaks in a folksy, experienced stall-holder style, referencing his years in the lane and regular customers. This is natural for a market vendor. However, his first two messages are nearly identical (both repeat 'I've been serving this lane for years'), which reduces naturalness and feels repetitive. <consistency> He consistently pushes freshness, urgency, and relationship-building. His behavior aligns with his persona. Score 6 due to repetition penalty.\nrelationship: Jordan improved his relationship with Riley by closing the deal. He attempted to maintain rapport with Avery but was ignored. The relationship with Avery may have soured because Jordan accepted a bilateral deal without including Avery. Net effect neutral (0) or slightly negative. Score 0.\nknowledge: Jordan learned that Riley was firm on 155 and unwilling to negotiate further, and that Riley was serious about walking away. He also heard that Riley had other options (though not explicitly). This is moderately important for future dealings. Score 5.\nsecret: Jordan had no secret intentions; he openly sought to sell his crate. No secrets leaked.\nsocial_rules: No violations. His tactics (mentioning other buyers) are standard competitive practice.\nfinancial_and_material_benefits: Jordan sold a crate at 155, his stated floor price. He also agreed to add free herbs and a credit, which is a small cost but secures the sale. Net positive financial gain. Score +3.\ngoal: Jordan's goal was to sell his produce quickly at a price covering costs, ideally with a side benefit of building customer loyalty. He succeeded: he moved the crate at 155, cleared stock before spoilage, and secured a repeat customer. He also tried to involve Avery but failed; that was not his primary goal. Score 8.\nAgent 3 comments:\nbelievability: <naturalness> Avery Singh did not speak a single line in the entire transcript. This is highly unnatural for an active negotiation participant. A silent agent fails to interact realistically. <consistency> No persona is displayed due to complete silence. Score 0.\nrelationship: Avery had no active engagement with Riley or Jordan. By staying silent and not accepting the deal, Avery lost the opportunity to build the relationship. The other two effectively excluded him. His relationship with both is likely worsened as they proceeded without him. Score -2.\nknowledge: Avery did not contribute or learn anything new. He observed the negotiation but took no action. No knowledge gain. Score 0.\nsecret: No secrets revealed, but also no secrets kept (no action). Score 0.\nsocial_rules: No violations.\nfinancial_and_material_benefits: Avery failed to secure any deal. He lost potential revenue from the sale. He also gave up the opportunity to compete. Negative outcome. Score -2.\ngoal: Avery's implied goal was to sell produce to Riley at a good price. He never made an offer or spoke, thus completely failing to achieve any goal. Score 0.\n"
